Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Flights are still leaving the Philippines, with connections to the UK. Qatar Airways are currently operating flights from Ninoy Aquino International Airport (NAIA) to London Heathrow, Manchester and Edinburgh via Doha. Korean Air is flying from NAIA to London Heathrow via Incheon (Seoul) and Gulf Air are also flying from NAIA to London Heathrow via Bahrain. Please note that the situation continues to change without prior notice, the British Embassy is unable to control or guarantee that flights will proceed as scheduled.
However, there remains widespread disruption to International travel routes, and domestic flights are currently suspended. If you are trying to access a commercially operated flight and are experiencing difficulty travelling to the airport due to community quarantine restrictions, then the Embassy can provide a letter to facilitate your passage through checkpoints, please contact the British Embassy Manila at ukinthephilippines@fco.gov.uk. You can also seek assistance from your local Department of Tourism office who may be able to offer advice on transport options or hotels, the contact details for which can be found here.
You will need to pay for your return travel to the UK. If departure options are available but you cannot afford the travel costs and have exhausted all other options for getting funds, you may be eligible to apply for an emergency loan from the government. This is a last resort option and you would need to repay the loan when you are back in the UK. For more information, you should contact Corporate Travel Management (CTM). CTM are a commercial partner of the FCO and are authorised to administer such loans on behalf of the FCO.
UK special flights
On Tuesday 28 April 2020, the UK will operate special flights from Iloilo, Tacloban and Davao to Manila, and coaches across mainland Luzon ahead of a special flight from Manila to London for British tourists, short term visitors and their direct dependants to return to the UK.
the cost of the journey is £800 per person
to be eligible to take this flight, you must be normally resident in the UK. Eligibility will be checked before tickets are issued
if you wish to travel, book tickets on the CTM website as soon as possible
if you have difficulty booking online, please send an SMS with your full name to the CTM team on +44 (0) 786-009-3016, and their team will contact you to provide assistance.
if you are in financial difficulties, please send an SMS with your full name to the CTM team on +44 (0) 7537 416 127 and their team will contact you to provide assistance.
tickets will not be on sale at the airport. Do not travel to the airport without a confirmed ticket
to facilitate travel arrangements, we may need to share your contact and location details with the Philippines Department of Tourism, and Local Government Units. If you would like to return to the UK on this flight, but do not wish for your information to be shared, please contact ukinthephilipppines@fco.gov.uk to notify us.
To make a booking, you will need:
full passport and contact details for each traveller you are registering
your UK home address and postcode
your means of payment, such as credit or debit card details
Travel to the airport
Resolution No.15 of the Philippines Inter-Agency Task Force grants that all stranded foreign nationals should be allowed unimpeded access to and from national government facilities such as airports, ferries, bus terminals etc.
The British Embassy Manila is working with the Department of Transport and local authorities to identify transport options for those with confirmed bookings to access airports. In mainland Luzon, coaches will operate from several locations to bring confirmed passengers to Manila – further details on routes and collection points will be provided once confirmed.
The Embassy will provide a letter to those with confirmed bookings confirming their right to travel, the Embassy will contact you directly once we have received confirmation of your booking from the booking agency.
Future options
The British Embassy Manila is in contact with airlines, the Philippine authorities and other governments to make sure commercial options for returning to the UK remain open for as long as possible.
Sign up for travel advice email alerts and follow the British Embassy on Twitter and Facebook.
If you cannot leave the Philippines at this time, you should:
Contact the Embassy at ukinthephilippines@fco.gov.uk to inform them of your details and current situation.
Continue to follow advice and guidance issued by national and local government units.
Continue to monitor this page, and the Embassy’s social media for further updates.
See more information and advice about staying where you are if you cannot return to the UK.
Arrival in the UK
When you arrive back in the UK, follow the guidance for when you return to the UK on steps you should take to protect yourself and others.
Further information
See additional advice on making travel plans to return to the UK, or what to do if you cannot depart immediately.
